vectorData.altText: 4) What is the function of muscle A?
That's right! Muscle A pulls horizontally across posterior aspect of the hip, therefore this muscle causes lateral rotation of the hip.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Muscles of the gluteal region act on the hip. Their specific action depends on their direction of pull across the joint. If you invest a moment to work out the following with your group, you will be rewarded by ultimately understanding (i.e. learning) the actions of these muscles, rather than memorizing them.

As illustrated, muscles that pull up on the lateral aspect of the greater trochanter (green arrow) abduct the hip. Muscles that pull horizontally across the back of the hip joint, perpendicular to the long axis of the femur (red arrow), laterally rotate the hip.
Some muscles, however, pull obliquely across the posterior aspect of the hip joint (blue arrow). Their pull can be deconstructed into two vectors (dotted arrows): one vector runs vertically, posterior to the hip and causes extension; the other runs horizontally, posterior to the hip, and causes lateral rotation     .

noting the position of a muscle relative to a joint (in this case, posterior) and its direction of pull (horizontal or vertical) is the key to understanding the action of muscles, rather than memorizing the action of muscles. Facts that are understood are retained; facts that are memorized are lost.
